txt_negFacts.title: Imam Husayn Shrine
txt_negFacts.fact: The Imam Husayn Shrine or the Place of Imam Husayn ibn Ali (Arabic: مَقَام ٱلْإِمَام ٱلْحُسَيْن ٱبْن عَلِيّ‎, romanized: Maqām al-ʾImām al-Ḥusayn ibn ʿAlīy) is the mosque and burial site of Husayn ibn Ali, the third Imam of Shia Islam, in the city of Karbala, Iraq.

txt_negFacts.title: Imam Ali Shrine
txt_negFacts.fact: The Sanctuary of Imam 'Ali (Arabic: حَرَم ٱلْإِمَام عَلِيّ‎, romanized: Ḥaram al-ʾImām ʿAlī), also known as the Mosque of 'Ali (Arabic: مَسْجِد عَلِيّ‎, romanized: Masjid ʿAlī), located in Najaf, Iraq, is a mosque which Shia Muslims believe contains the tomb of'Alī ibn Abī Tālib.

txt_negFacts.title: Holiest sites in Shia Islam
txt_negFacts.fact: Imam Reza Shrine in Mashhad, Iran contains the tomb of Ali al-Ridha, the eighth Shia Imam. Ali al-Ridha is believed, by members of the Shia, to have been poisoned there upon the orders of Caliph Al-Ma'mun and the place was subsequently called, Mashhad ar-Ridhā (the place of martyrdom of Ali al-Ridha).

txt_negFacts.title: Holiest sites in Shia Islam
txt_negFacts.fact: The Al-Askari Shrine in Samarra, Iraq contains the tombs of Ali al-Hadi, tenth Shia Imam and Hasan al-Askari, eleventh Shia Imam. Hakimah Khātūn, sister of Ali al-Hadi and Narjis, mother of Muhammad al-Mahdi are also buried within the mosque.

txt_negFacts.title: Holiest sites in Shia Islam

txt_negFacts.title: Shia Islam
txt_negFacts.fact: After the four holy cities of Islam (Mecca, Medina, Jerusalem and Damascus) Najaf, Karbala and Qom are the most revered by Shia Muslims. The Imam Ali Mosque in Najaf, Imam Husayn Shrine in Karbala and Fatima Masumeh Shrine in Qom are very essential for Shias.

txt_negFacts.title: Mars (mythology)
txt_negFacts.fact: The earliest center in Rome for cultivating Mars as a deity was the Altar of Mars (Ara Martis) in the Campus Martius ("Field of Mars") outside the sacred boundary of Rome (pomerium).

txt_negFacts.title: Campus Martius
txt_negFacts.fact: The Campus Martius (Latin for the "Field of Mars", Italian Campo Marzio) was a publicly owned area of ancient Rome about 2 square kilometres (490 acres) in extent.

txt_negFacts.title: Secular Games
txt_negFacts.fact: The Games were revived in 17 BC by Rome's first emperor Augustus, with the nocturnal sacrifices on the Campus Martius now transferred to the Moerae (fates), the Ilythiae (goddesses of childbirth), and Terra Mater ("Mother Earth").

txt_negFacts.title: Campus Martius
txt_negFacts.fact: The Campus Martius (Latin for the "Field of Mars", Italian Campo Marzio) was a publicly owned area of ancient Rome about 2 square kilometres (490 acres) in extent. In the Middle Ages, it was the most populous area of Rome.

txt_negFacts.title: Campus Martius
txt_negFacts.fact: After the death of Alexander the Great in 324 BC or the beginning of the "wave of Hellenism" there was a drastic increase in terms building construction within the city of Rome. In the case of Campus Martius, specifically during the "wave of Hellenism", there were seven temples built.

txt_negFacts.title: Campus Martius
txt_negFacts.fact: Some of the most significant temples of the campus are the rectangular temples of Largo di Torre Argentina, located in the southern part of the Campus Martius. It is a religious complex composed of four temples: Temple Juturna, Temple Fortuna Huiusce Diei, Temple Feronia, and Temple Lares Permarini.

txt_negFacts.title: History of Rome
txt_negFacts.fact: The population, without imports of grain and oil from Sicily, shrank to less than 50,000 concentrated near the Tiber and around the Campus Martius, abandoning those districts without water supply. There is a legend, significant though untrue, that there was a moment where no one remained living in Rome.

txt_negFacts.title: Campus Martius
txt_negFacts.fact: For possibly the first time Campus Martius and all of Rome faced a period where they moved away from the classical ways of architecture.

txt_negFacts.title: Regio IX Circus Flaminius
txt_negFacts.fact: As the lands beyond the Servian Wall were traditionally not held to be part of the city of Rome, the Campus Martius also possessed several tombs, which were not permitted to be placed within the traditional limits of the city.

txt_negFacts.title: Campus Martius
txt_negFacts.fact: Alongside Rome, temples built within the Campus Martius faced a “fundamental change in stylistic direction” during the latter half of the first century on.

txt_negFacts.title: Campus Martius
txt_negFacts.fact: As the population of Rome greatly increased in the Middle Ages, the Campus Martius became a crowded multi-cultural place where many foreigners settled.

txt_negFacts.title: Campus Martius
txt_negFacts.fact: After the Renaissance, as was the case for the rest of Rome, the Campus Martius did not change much; there were no other great building projects and the population decreased.

txt_negFacts.title: Mars (mythology)
txt_negFacts.fact: Mars's altar in the Campus Martius, the area of Rome that took its name from him, was supposed to have been dedicated by Numa, the peace-loving semi-legendary second king of Rome.

txt_negFacts.title: Mars (mythology)
txt_negFacts.fact: The panel of the Ara Pacis on which he appears would have faced the Campus Martius, reminding viewers that Mars was the god whose altar Numa established there, that is, the god of Rome's oldest civic and military institutions.

txt_negFacts.title: Campus Martius
txt_negFacts.fact: The main road connecting Rome to the rest of Europe was the Via Cassia, entering Rome through the Porta del Popolo in the northern part of the Campus Martius.

txt_negFacts.title: Campus Martius
txt_negFacts.fact: After the Renaissance, as was the case for the rest of Rome, the Campus Martius did not change much; there were no other great building projects and the population decreased. This was reversed after Rome became capital of the newly established  Kingdom of Italy in 1870.

txt_negFacts.fact: The Eiffel Tower ( EYE-fəl; French: tour Eiffel [tuʁ‿ɛfɛl] (listen)) is a wrought-iron lattice tower on the Champ de Mars in Paris, France. It is named after the engineer Gustave Eiffel, whose company designed and built the tower.

txt_negFacts.title: Eiffel Tower in popular culture
txt_negFacts.fact: They later realize that Eiffel developed the tower to trap ghosts, making the Eiffel Tower the world's largest "ghost containment unit". By story's end, the ghosts were transmitted to the Ghostbuster's Primary Containment Unit back in New York, essentially de-haunting the Tower.

txt_negFacts.title: Eiffel Tower
txt_negFacts.fact: Graffitists were also catered for: sheets of paper were mounted on the walls each day for visitors to record their impressions of the tower. Gustave Eiffel described some of the responses as vraiment curieuse ("truly curious").

txt_negFacts.title: Eiffel Tower in popular culture
txt_negFacts.fact: In the 2010 computer-animated comedy film Despicable Me, the Eiffel Tower is shown being projected by the French Army and a mime after the Great Pyramid of Giza is stolen by Vector. Later on, Gru shows the Minions that they accomplished in stealing the tower, albeit the replica from Paris Las Vegas.

txt_negFacts.title: Eiffel Tower in popular culture
txt_negFacts.fact: The plot of Night of the New Magicians from the Magic Tree House book series by Mary Pope Osborne had the protagonists searching the 1889 World's Fair beneath the newly constructed Eiffel Tower for Alexander Graham Bell, Louis Pasteur, Thomas Edison, and Gustave Eiffel, who had all gathered atop the tower.

txt_negFacts.title: Eiffel Tower in popular culture

txt_negFacts.fact: In a commitment ceremony Erika Eiffel, an American woman, "married" the Eiffel Tower; her relationship with the tower has been the subject of extensive global publicity.

txt_negFacts.title: Eiffel Tower in popular culture

txt_negFacts.title: Eiffel Tower in popular culture
txt_negFacts.fact: In a Bill Nye the Science Guy episode titled "Magnetism", Bill Nye mentions two examples of "very tall metal towers" and the first one is the Eiffel Tower. The tower is shown onscreen when he mentions it.

txt_negFacts.title: List of the 72 names on the Eiffel Tower
txt_negFacts.fact: On the Eiffel Tower, 72 names of French scientists, engineers, and mathematicians are engraved in recognition of their contributions. Gustave Eiffel chose this "invocation of science" because of his concern over the protests against the tower.

txt_negFacts.title: Eiffel Tower
txt_negFacts.fact: The tower is painted in three shades: lighter at the top, getting progressively darker towards the bottom to complement the Parisian sky. It was originally reddish brown; this changed in 1968 to a bronze colour known as "Eiffel Tower Brown".

txt_negFacts.title: Roman numerals
txt_negFacts.fact: Roman numerals are essentially a decimal or "base ten" number system, but instead of place value notation (in which place-keeping zeros enable a digit to represent different powers of ten) the system uses a set of symbols with fixed values, including "built in" powers of ten.

txt_negFacts.title: Greek numerals
txt_negFacts.fact: Greek numerals, also known as Ionic, Ionian, Milesian, or Alexandrian numerals, are a system of writing numbers using the letters of the Greek alphabet. txt_negFacts.title: Greenwood Lake

txt_negFacts.title: Ontario
txt_negFacts.fact: In the northeastern parts of Ontario, extending south as far as Kirkland Lake, the cold waters of Hudson Bay depress summer temperatures, making it cooler than other locations at similar latitudes. txt_negFacts.title: The Valley of Wyoming
txt_negFacts.fact: The Valley of Wyoming is an 1865 painting by American painter Jasper Francis Cropsey. Cropsey, a prominent landscape painter, rendered Valley so as to depict the Wyoming Valley in Northeastern Pennsylvania.

txt_negFacts.title: Lake Ontario

txt_negFacts.title: Lake Ontario

txt_negFacts.title: Indigo
txt_negFacts.fact: The Early Modern English word indigo referred to the dye, not to the color (hue) itself, and indigo is not traditionally part of the basic color-naming system. Modern sources place indigo in the electromagnetic spectrum between 420 and 450 nanometers, which lies on the short-wave side of color wheel (RGB) blue, towards (spectral) violet.

txt_negFacts.title: Indigo
txt_negFacts.fact: The color "electric indigo" is a bright and saturated color between the traditional indigo and violet. This is the brightest color indigo that can be approximated on a computer screen; it is a color located between the (primary) blue and the color violet of the RGB color wheel.

txt_negFacts.title: Computer monitor
txt_negFacts.fact: Color depth - measured in bits per primary color or bits for all colors. Those with 10 bpc (bits per channel) or more can display more shades of color (approximately 1 billion shades) than traditional 8 bpc monitors (approximately 16.8 million shades or colors), and can do so more precisely without having to resort to dithering.

txt_negFacts.title: RGB color model
txt_negFacts.fact: Initially, the limited color depth of most video hardware led to a limited color palette of 216 RGB colors, defined by the Netscape Color Cube. With the predominance of 24-bit displays, the use of the full 16.7 million colors of the HTML RGB color code no longer poses problems for most viewers.

txt_negFacts.title: Computer monitor
txt_negFacts.fact: Contrast ratio is the ratio of the luminosity of the brightest color (white) to that of the darkest color (black) that the monitor is capable of producing simultaneously. For example, a ratio of 20,000∶1 means that the brightest shade (white) is 20,000 times brighter than its darkest shade (black).

txt_negFacts.title: RGB color model

txt_negFacts.title: German Tank Museum
txt_negFacts.fact: The German Tank Museum (German: Deutsches Panzermuseum Munster (DPM)) is an armoured fighting vehicle museum in Munster, Germany, the location of the Munster Training Area camp (not to be confused with the city of Münster). Its main aim is the documentation of the history of German armoured troops since 1917.

txt_negFacts.title: Deutsches Historisches Museum

txt_negFacts.title: Deansgate Square

The site is just south of Deansgate railway station and north of the Mancunian Way, bounded by Old Deansgate, Pond Street, Owen Street and the River Medlock.

txt_negFacts.title: World's littlest skyscraper

txt_negFacts.title: Beach in Pourville
txt_negFacts.fact: La plage à Pourville, soleil couchant)  is a painting by French artist Claude Monet. It is one of an 1882 series of oil-on-canvas works by Monet in the small seaside resort of Pourville-sur-Mer (now part of the commune of Hautot-sur-Mer), near Dieppe in northern France.

txt_negFacts.title: Las Vegas algorithm
txt_negFacts.fact: Las Vegas algorithms were introduced by László Babai in 1979, in the context of the graph isomorphism problem, as a dual to Monte Carlo algorithms. Babai introduced the term "Las Vegas algorithm" alongside an example involving coin flips: the algorithm depends on a series of independent coin flips, and there is a small chance of failure (no result).

txt_negFacts.title: Park MGM
txt_negFacts.fact: The Monte Carlo was converted into Park MGM between late 2016 and 2018, with the upper floors being converted into a boutique hotel, NoMad Las Vegas. The hotel, formerly named to invoke the Place du Casino in Monte Carlo, featured chandelier domes, marble floors, neoclassical arches, ornate fountains, and gas-lit promenades.

txt_negFacts.title: Las Vegas algorithm
txt_negFacts.fact: Babai introduced the term "Las Vegas algorithm" alongside an example involving coin flips: the algorithm depends on a series of independent coin flips, and there is a small chance of failure (no result). However, in contrast to Monte Carlo algorithms, the Las Vegas algorithm can guarantee the correctness of any reported result.

txt_negFacts.title: Las Vegas algorithm
txt_negFacts.fact: Since Las Vegas does not end until it finds 1 in the array, it does not gamble with the correctness but run-time. On the other hand, Monte Carlo runs 300 times, which means it is impossible to know that Monte Carlo will find "1" in the array within 300 times of loops until it actually executes the code.

txt_negFacts.title: Monte Carlo algorithm
txt_negFacts.fact: The term "Monte Carlo" was first introduced in 1947 by Nicholas Metropolis. Las Vegas algorithms are a dual of Monte Carlo algorithms that never return an incorrect answer--however, they may make random choices as part of their working.

txt_negFacts.title: Las Vegas Strip
txt_negFacts.fact: In 2018, the Monte Carlo Resort and Casino was renamed the Park MGM and in 2019, the SLS changed its name back to Sahara Las Vegas. In 2021, the Pinball Hall of Fame moved near the "Fabulous Las Vegas" sign at the south end of the Strip.

txt_negFacts.title: Eataly
txt_negFacts.fact: In June 2016, it was announced that an Eataly location would open in 2018 at the Park MGM casino in Las Vegas (formerly the Monte Carlo). Eataly will fill approximately 40,000 square feet on the southern edge of the resort and The Park-facing side will become the main pedestrian entrance into the Park MGM casino.

txt_negFacts.title: The Venetian Las Vegas
txt_negFacts.fact: In October 2005, Blue Man Group opened at the Blue Man Theatre and continued performing there until September 2012, when the show relocated to the Monte Carlo resort. On June 24, 2006, the show, Phantom: The Las Vegas Spectacular, opened at a new Paris Opera House styled theatre at The Venetian.

txt_negFacts.title: Las Vegas algorithm
txt_negFacts.fact: However, it is hard to convert a Monte Carlo algorithm to a Las Vegas algorithm without a way to test the algorithm.

txt_negFacts.title: Las Vegas algorithm
txt_negFacts.fact: A Las Vegas algorithm can be converted into a Monte Carlo algorithm by running it for set time and generating a random answer when it fails to terminate.

txt_negFacts.title: Las Vegas algorithm
txt_negFacts.fact: If a deterministic way to test for correctness is available, then it is possible to turn a Monte Carlo algorithm into a Las Vegas algorithm.

txt_negFacts.title: Las Vegas algorithm
txt_negFacts.fact: However, it is hard to convert a Monte Carlo algorithm to a Las Vegas algorithm without a way to test the algorithm. On the other hand, changing a Las Vegas algorithm to a Monte Carlo algorithm is easy.

txt_negFacts.title: Las Vegas algorithm
txt_negFacts.fact: Las Vegas algorithms can be contrasted with Monte Carlo algorithms, in which the resources used are bounded but the answer may be incorrect with a certain (typically small) probability.

txt_negFacts.title: Las Vegas algorithm
txt_negFacts.fact: If a deterministic way to test for correctness is available, then it is possible to turn a Monte Carlo algorithm into a Las Vegas algorithm. However, it is hard to convert a Monte Carlo algorithm to a Las Vegas algorithm without a way to test the algorithm.

txt_negFacts.title: Monte Carlo algorithm
txt_negFacts.fact: Las Vegas algorithms are a dual of Monte Carlo algorithms that never return an incorrect answer--however, they may make random choices as part of their working.

txt_negFacts.title: Hollywood
txt_negFacts.fact: Street limits of the Hollywood neighborhood are: north, Hollywood Boulevard from La Brea Avenue to the east boundary of Wattles Garden Park and Franklin Avenue between Bonita and Western avenues; east, Western Avenue; south, Melrose Avenue, and west, La Brea Avenue or the West Hollywood city line.

txt_negFacts.title: Koreatown, Los Angeles
txt_negFacts.fact: The Koreatown Regional Commercial Center runs along Olympic Boulevard and is "generally bounded by Eighth Street on the north, Twelfth Street on the south, Western Avenue on the west, and continues east towards Vermont Avenue", according to the Wilshire Community Plan of the City of Los Angeles.

txt_negFacts.title: Western Avenue (Los Angeles)
txt_negFacts.fact: The northern terminus of Western is north of Franklin Avenue in the Los Feliz district, at the base of the Hollywood Hills. txt_negFacts.title: Hollywood
txt_negFacts.fact: In 1910, the city voted for a merger with Los Angeles in order to secure an adequate water supply and to gain access to the L.A. sewer system. With annexation, the name of Prospect Avenue was changed to Hollywood Boulevard and all the street numbers were also changed.

txt_negFacts.title: Western (genre)

txt_negFacts.title: Western (genre)

txt_negFacts.title: Hollywood Sign
txt_negFacts.fact: In films and television shows, the Hollywood Sign is often shown getting damaged or destroyed from the events of a particular scene; period pieces may show just the "LAND" portion of the original sign being destroyed.

txt_negFacts.title: Hollywood Sign
txt_negFacts.fact: On February 11, 2010, as part of a campaign to help raise money and with the full support of both the city and the Hollywood Sign Trust, the organization covered each letter of the sign with large banners reading "SAVE THE PEAK".

txt_negFacts.fact: However, Western Avenue extends intermittently through the Southland to the Will / Kankakee county border in unincorporated Will Township. Within Chicago's grid street system, Western Avenue is 2400 West, three miles west of State Street (0 East/West).

txt_negFacts.title: Koreatown, Los Angeles
txt_negFacts.fact: The city of Los Angeles has set the official boundaries for Koreatown as Vermont Avenue on the east, Western Avenue on the west, Third Street on the north, and Olympic Boulevard on the south. A business corridor running about 3/4 of a mile along Western Avenue to Rosewood Avenue is also included as part of Koreatown.

txt_negFacts.title: Hollywood Reservoir
txt_negFacts.fact: The reservoir and surrounding neighborhood are overlooked by the Hollywood Sign. txt_negFacts.title: Western Avenue (Los Angeles)
txt_negFacts.fact: Around the Pico Boulevard, Olympic Boulevard, and Wilshire Boulevard intersections, Western Avenue passes through Koreatown. Further north, Western Avenue passes through the East Hollywood district.

txt_negFacts.title: Hollywood Sign
txt_negFacts.fact: It was intended only to last a year and a half, but after the rise of American cinema in Los Angeles during the Golden Age of Hollywood, the sign became an internationally recognized symbol and was left there.

txt_negFacts.title: John and Mable Ringling Museum of Art
txt_negFacts.fact: The John and Mable Ringling Museum of Art is the official state art museum of Florida, located in Sarasota, Florida. It was established in 1927 as the legacy of Mable Burton Ringling and John Ringling for the people of Florida.

txt_negFacts.title: Ca' d'Zan
txt_negFacts.fact: Ca' d'Zan is a Venetian Gothic revival residence in Sarasota, Florida, adjacent to the Sarasota Bay. The residence was the winter home of the American circus owner, developer and art collector John Ringling and his wife Mable.

txt_negFacts.title: John and Mable Ringling Museum of Art

txt_negFacts.title: Asolo Repertory Theatre
txt_negFacts.fact: In 1949 the museum director of the John and Mable Ringling Museum of Art learned of the theatre's existence and saw the theatre as an ideal acquisition for the museum. The State of Florida agreed and purchased the theatre which was crated and shipped to Sarasota, Florida.

txt_negFacts.title: John and Mable Ringling Museum of Art
txt_negFacts.fact: The next stop for the railcar was The John and Mable Ringling Museum in Sarasota Florida. An anonymous donation of $100,000 then brought the Wisconsin's interiors back to its Gilded Age sheen, work which was done right at the museum.

txt_negFacts.title: John Ringling

txt_negFacts.title: Hope Township, New Jersey
txt_negFacts.fact: Hope Township is a township in Warren County, New Jersey, United States. As of the 2010 United States Census, the township's population was 1,952, reflecting an increase of 61 (+3.2%) from the 1,891 counted in the 2000 Census, which had in turn increased by 172 (+10.0%) from the 1,719 counted in the 1990 Census.

txt_negFacts.title: Interstate Highway System
txt_negFacts.fact: To control costs, California began to incorporate exit numbers on its freeways in 2002—Interstate, U.S., and state routes alike. Caltrans commonly installs exit number signage only when a freeway or interchange is built, reconstructed, retrofitted, or repaired, and it is usually tacked onto the top-right corner of an already existing sign.

txt_negFacts.title: Knowlton Township, New Jersey
txt_negFacts.fact: Interstate 80 (Bergen-Passaic Expressway) is the main east–west limited access road, passing through the township for 7.24 miles (11.65 km) with a junction at Routes 94 and 46. Route 94 passes through the northern portion of the township for 3.92 miles (6.31 km).

txt_negFacts.title: Knowlton Township, New Jersey
txt_negFacts.fact: Much of Knowlton's development after 1850 can be traced to the presence of the five railroad lines that criss-crossed the township: the Delaware, Lackawanna & Western Railroad's Old Road and, later, the Lackawanna Cut-Off; the New York, Susquehanna and Western Railway; the Lehigh & New England Railroad; and the Blairstown Railway.

txt_negFacts.title: Knowlton Township, New Jersey
txt_negFacts.fact: Portions of the township were taken to form Hope Township (April 8, 1839) and Blairstown Township (April 14, 1845).Knowlton's name is variously attributed to Thomas Knowlton, a Colonel in the Continental Army during the American Revolutionary War who was killed in action at the Battle of Harlem Heights, or to the knolls that characterize the area.

txt_negFacts.title: Interstate Highway System
txt_negFacts.fact: If multiple exits occur within the same mile, letter suffixes may be appended to the numbers in alphabetical order starting with A.   A small number of interstate highways (mostly in the Northeastern United States) use sequential-based exit numbering schemes (where each exit is numbered in order starting with 1, without regard for the mile markers on the road).

txt_negFacts.title: Hope Township, New Jersey

txt_negFacts.title: Blairstown, New Jersey

txt_negFacts.title: Exit sign
txt_negFacts.fact: In Australia, New Zealand and most European countries pictograms are used in place of the word "exit". European sign directive 92/58/EEC of 24 June 1992 indicates that the signs should be green in color to indicate a safe place of exit.

txt_negFacts.title: Interstate Highway System
txt_negFacts.fact: Signs with the shield alone are placed periodically throughout each Interstate as reassurance markers. These signs usually measure 36 inches (91 cm) high, and is 36 inches (91 cm) wide for two-digit Interstates or 45 inches (110 cm) for three-digit Interstates.

txt_negFacts.title: Exit sign
txt_negFacts.fact: Exit signs are designed to be absolutely unmistakable and understandable to anyone. In the past, this generally meant exit signs that show the word "EXIT" or the equivalent in the local language, but increasingly exit signs around the world are in pictogram form, with or without supplementary text.

txt_negFacts.fact: An investigation found that Emergency and Exit lights were not properly illuminated, and the landlord was fined about $20,000 for "not properly illuminating exit signs, and having no record of emergency lighting tests", and another $50,000 for other infractions to the code.

txt_negFacts.title: Interstate 80
txt_negFacts.fact: The longest straight stretch of Interstate anywhere in the Interstate Highway System is the approximately 72 miles (116 km) of I-80 occurring between exit 318 in the Grand Island area and mile marker 390 near Lincoln. txt_negFacts.title: Common chiffchaff

txt_negFacts.title: District line
txt_negFacts.fact: On the main line, there are cross-platform interchanges at Acton Town, Hammersmith and Barons Court stations, after which the Piccadilly line tracks descend into tunnels, while the District line becomes two tracks through West Kensington station.

txt_negFacts.title: List of London Underground stations
txt_negFacts.fact: There are two instances where two separate stations share the same name: there is one Edgware Road station on the Circle, District and Hammersmith & City lines and another Edgware Road on the Bakerloo line, and there is one Hammersmith station on the District and Piccadilly lines and another Hammersmith station on the Circle and Hammersmith & City lines.

txt_negFacts.title: Barons Court tube station
txt_negFacts.fact: West of the station, both Piccadilly line and District line continue to Hammersmith station. The station is located in a deep, brick sided cutting.

txt_negFacts.title: Barons Court tube station
txt_negFacts.fact: East of the station, the Piccadilly line descends into tunnel towards Earl's Court and the District line continues on the surface to West Kensington. West of the station, both Piccadilly line and District line continue to Hammersmith station.

txt_negFacts.title: Barons Court tube station
txt_negFacts.fact: Barons Court is a London Underground station in West Kensington in the London Borough of Hammersmith and Fulham, Greater London. This station serves the District line and the Piccadilly line.

txt_negFacts.title: Barons Court tube station
txt_negFacts.fact: This station serves the District line and the Piccadilly line. Barons Court is between West Kensington and Hammersmith on the District line, and between Earl's Court and Hammersmith on the Piccadilly line and is in Travelcard Zone 2.

txt_negFacts.title: Hammersmith tube station (Circle and Hammersmith & City lines)
txt_negFacts.fact: Part of this viaduct is still visible from District and Piccadilly line trains west of the Hammersmith station on those lines. The extension closed on 31 December 1906 shortly after the introduction of electric trains on the line.

txt_negFacts.title: Barons Court tube station
txt_negFacts.fact: The station is the last open air stop for eastbound trains on the Piccadilly line until Arnos Grove and has cross-platform interchange with the District line.

txt_negFacts.title: Barons Court tube station
txt_negFacts.fact: Barons Court is between West Kensington and Hammersmith on the District line, and between Earl's Court and Hammersmith on the Piccadilly line and is in Travelcard Zone 2. East of the station, the Piccadilly line descends into tunnel towards Earl's Court and the District line continues in a cutting to West Kensington.

txt_negFacts.title: Hammersmith tube station (District and Piccadilly lines)
txt_negFacts.fact: Hammersmith is a London Underground station in Hammersmith. It is on the District line between Barons Court and Ravenscourt Park, and on the Piccadilly line between Barons Court and Acton Town or Turnham Green at very early morning and late evening hours.

txt_negFacts.title: Earl's Court tube station
txt_negFacts.fact: Platforms 5 serves the Piccadilly line eastbound to Cockfosters, and platform 6 serves the line westbound to Uxbridge and Heathrow Airport. The station has a dedicated regulating room which has served as the principal point for signalling on the Piccadilly and District lines since the 1960s.

txt_negFacts.title: District line
txt_negFacts.fact: The whole District line service could not run through Aldgate East as this station was also served by Hammersmith & City trains, so some trains terminated at a bay platform at Mansion House, leaving the line east to Tower Hill overcrowded. Tower Hill station was also cramped, so the station was rebuilt with three platforms on a new site.

txt_negFacts.title: Acton Town tube station
txt_negFacts.fact: In 1931 and 1932 the station was rebuilt again in preparation for transferring the Uxbridge branch service from the District line to the Piccadilly line.

txt_negFacts.title: Hammersmith tube station (District and Piccadilly lines)
txt_negFacts.fact: On 17 October 2003 a Piccadilly Line train derailed in a tunnel just outside the station, when the wheels of the second-to-last carriage left the tracks. There were no injuries, but there was some damage to rails and sleepers.

txt_negFacts.title: Piccadilly line
txt_negFacts.fact: By then, most Piccadilly line trains continued beyond Hammersmith, and District line trains to Hounslow were reduced to off-peak shuttles to Acton Town.

txt_negFacts.title: Barons Court tube station
txt_negFacts.fact: East of the station, the Piccadilly line descends into tunnel towards Earl's Court and the District line continues in a cutting to West Kensington.

txt_negFacts.title: Russulaceae
txt_negFacts.fact: The genera Lactarius, Lactifluus, Multifurca and Russula form a mutualistic ectomycorrhizal root symbiosis with trees and shrubs, exchanging mineral nutrients for photosynthetic sugar. txt_negFacts.title: Leccinum scabrum

txt_negFacts.title: Mantled howler
txt_negFacts.fact: The mantled howler (Alouatta palliata), or golden-mantled howling monkey, is a species of howler monkey, a type of New World monkey, from Central and South America. It is one of the monkey species most often seen and heard in the wild in Central America.

txt_negFacts.title: List of Central American monkey species
txt_negFacts.fact: At least seven monkey species are native to Central America.   An eighth species, the Coiba Island howler (Alouatta coibensis) is often recognized, but some authorities treat it as a subspecies of the mantled howler, (A. palliata).

txt_negFacts.title: Mantled howler

txt_negFacts.title: Mantled howler
txt_negFacts.fact: However, the mantled howler is a relatively inactive monkey. It sleeps or rests the entire night and about three quarters of the day.

txt_negFacts.title: Mantled howler

txt_negFacts.title: Mantled howler
txt_negFacts.fact: The three color vision exhibited by the mantled howler is believed to be related to its dietary preferences, allowing it to distinguish young leaves, which tend to be more reddish, from more mature leaves.

txt_negFacts.title: Guatemalan black howler

txt_negFacts.fact: The Guatemalan black howler shares several adaptations with other species of howler monkey that allow it to pursue a folivorous diet (mostly leaves).

txt_negFacts.title: Bias against left-handed people
txt_negFacts.fact: The origin of this term is disputed, but some suggest it is derived from the Latin cacare, in reference to the habit of performing ablutions with the left hand, leaving the right hand "clean".

txt_negFacts.title: Right hand of God
txt_negFacts.fact: In Jesus' parable "The Sheep and the Goats", the sheep and goats are separated with the sheep on the right hand of God and the goats on the left hand.

txt_negFacts.title: Morganatic marriage
txt_negFacts.fact: The German name was Ehe zur linken Hand ("marriage by the left hand") and the husband gave his left hand during the wedding ceremony instead of the right.

txt_negFacts.title: Left- and right-hand traffic
txt_negFacts.fact: Left-hand traffic (LHT) and right-hand traffic (RHT) are the practices, in bidirectional traffic, of keeping to the left side or to the right side of the road, respectively.

txt_negFacts.title: Left- and right-hand traffic
txt_negFacts.fact: Left-hand traffic (LHT) and right-hand traffic (RHT) are the practices, in bidirectional traffic, of keeping to the left side or to the right side of the road, respectively. They are fundamental to traffic flow, and are sometimes referred to as the rule of the road.

txt_negFacts.title: Handedness
txt_negFacts.fact: In his book Right-Hand, Left-Hand, Chris McManus of University College London argues that the proportion of left-handers is increasing, and that an above-average quota of high achievers have been left-handed.

txt_negFacts.title: Bias against left-handed people
txt_negFacts.fact: The right hand is commonly known in contradistinction from the left, as the hand used for eating. In many religions, including Christianity, the right hand of God is the favored hand.

txt_negFacts.title: Left- and right-hand traffic
txt_negFacts.fact: It has been suggested that wagon-drivers whipped their horses with their right hand, and thus sat on the left hand side of the wagon, as in RHT.

txt_negFacts.title: Handedness
txt_negFacts.fact: During this era, children were taught to write with a dip pen. While a right-hander could smoothly drag the pen across paper from left to right, a dip pen could not easily be pushed across by the left hand without digging into the paper and making blots and stains.

txt_negFacts.title: Left-hand path and right-hand path
txt_negFacts.fact: In some definitions, the Left-Hand Path is equated with malicious black magic or black shamanism, while the Right-Hand Path with benevolent white magic.

txt_negFacts.title: Fleming's right-hand rule
txt_negFacts.fact: There is also a Fleming's left-hand rule (for electric motors). The appropriately handed rule can be recalled from the letter "g", which is in "right" and "generator".

txt_negFacts.title: Bias against left-handed people
txt_negFacts.fact: Currently, amongst Muslims and in some societies including Nepal and India it is still customary to use the left hand for cleaning oneself with water after defecating. The right hand is commonly known in contradistinction from the left, as the hand used for eating.

txt_negFacts.title: Bias against left-handed people
txt_negFacts.fact: In Ghana, pointing, gesturing, giving or receiving items with the left hand is considered taboo or rude. A person giving directions will put their left hand behind them and even physically strain to point with their right hand if necessary.

txt_negFacts.title: Statue of Zeus at Olympia
txt_negFacts.fact: Its right hand held a small chryselephantine statue of crowned Nike, goddess of victory; its left a scepter inlaid with many metals, supporting an eagle.

txt_negFacts.title: Handedness
txt_negFacts.fact: In two studies, Diana Deutsch found that left-handers, particularly those with mixed hand preference, performed significantly better than right-handers in musical memory tasks.

txt_negFacts.title: Bias against left-handed people
txt_negFacts.fact: Handheld circular saws are made almost exclusively for right-handers, with the motor and grip on the right side. If held in the left hand, it is impossible for the operator to see what they are cutting.

txt_negFacts.fact: The Eccrinales and Amoebidiales are opisthokont protists, previously thought to be zygomycete fungi. Other groups now in Opisthokonta (e.g., Corallochytrium, Ichthyosporea) were also at given time classified as fungi.

txt_negFacts.title: Marine fungi
txt_negFacts.fact: Fungi from Verrucariales also form marine lichens with the brown algae Petroderma maculiforme, and have a symbiotic relationship with seaweed like (rockweed) and Blidingia minima, where the algae are the dominant components. The fungi is thought to help the rockweeds to resist desiccation when exposed to air.

txt_negFacts.title: Fungus
txt_negFacts.fact: The "Fungi imperfecti" (fungi lacking the perfect or sexual stage) or Deuteromycota comprise all the species that lack an observable sexual cycle. Deuteromycota is not an accepted taxonomic clade and is now taken to mean simply fungi that lack a known sexual stage.

txt_negFacts.title: Marine fungi
txt_negFacts.fact: They are divided into two major groups; obligate marine fungi and facultative marine fungi. Obligate marine fungi are adapted to reproduce in the aquatic environment, while facultative marine fungi can grow in aquatic as well as terrestrial environments.

txt_negFacts.title: Fungus
txt_negFacts.fact: Certain species of the genus Pythium, which are oomycetes, have potential as biocontrol agents against certain fungi. Fungi can also act as mycoparasites or antagonists of other fungi, such as Hypomyces chrysospermus, which grows on bolete mushrooms.

txt_negFacts.title: Fungus
txt_negFacts.fact: Abundant worldwide, most fungi are inconspicuous because of the small size of their structures, and their cryptic lifestyles in soil or on dead matter. Fungi include symbionts of plants, animals, or other fungi and also parasites.

txt_negFacts.title: Marine fungi
txt_negFacts.fact: Fungi represent a large and diverse group of microorganisms in microbiological communities in the marine environment and have an important role in nutrient cycling. They are divided into two major groups; obligate marine fungi and facultative marine fungi.

txt_negFacts.title: Marine fungi
txt_negFacts.fact: To date, a relatively small percentage of described species are associated with marine environments, with ∼1,100 species retrieved exclusively from the marine environment. txt_negFacts.title: Fungus

txt_negFacts.title: Nidulariaceae
txt_negFacts.fact: The Nidulariaceae ('nidulus' - small nest) are a family of fungi in the order Agaricales. Commonly known as the bird's nest fungi, their fruiting bodies resemble tiny egg-filled birds' nests.

txt_negFacts.title: Basidiospore

txt_negFacts.fact: St. Peter's Basilica is one of the papal basilicas (previously styled "patriarchal basilicas") and one of the four Major Basilicas of Rome, the other Major Basilicas (all of which are also Papal Basilicas) being the Basilicas of St. John Lateran, St. Mary Major, and St. Paul outside the Walls.

txt_negFacts.title: John the Deacon of the Lateran
txt_negFacts.fact: John lived in the second half of the 12th century, and served as a deacon and canon of the Basilica of St. John Lateran. txt_negFacts.title: Organ stop
txt_negFacts.fact: Organ pipes are physically organized within the organ into sets according to note and timbre. A set of pipes producing the same timbre for each note is called a rank, while each key on a pipe organ controls a note which may be sounded by different ranks of pipes, alone or in combination.

txt_negFacts.title: Holy door
txt_negFacts.fact: The holy door of St. Peter's Basilica was opened by the Pope on 24 December 1999 while the doors of St. John Lateran and St. Mary Major were opened on 25 December and 1 January, respectively. The community is bounded by Empire Boulevard (formerly Malbone Street) to the north, Clarkson Avenue to the south, New York Avenue to the east, and Ocean Avenue/Prospect Park to the west.

txt_negFacts.title: Park Slope

txt_negFacts.title: Brooklyn
txt_negFacts.fact: Yvette Clarke (first elected in 2006) represents New York's 9th congressional district, which includes the central and southern Brooklyn neighborhoods of Crown Heights, East Flatbush, Flatbush, Midwood, Park Slope, Prospect Heights, Prospect Lefferts Gardens, and Windsor Terrace.

txt_negFacts.title: Prospect Park Zoo
txt_negFacts.fact: The Prospect Park Zoo is part of the Wildlife Conservation Society, an integrated network of four zoos and an aquarium spread throughout New York City. Located at 450 Flatbush Avenue, across from the Brooklyn Botanic Garden, the zoo is situated on a 12-acre (4.9 ha) plot somewhat lower than street level in Prospect Park.

txt_negFacts.title: Prospect Lefferts Gardens
txt_negFacts.fact: The community is bounded by Empire Boulevard (formerly Malbone Street) to the north, Clarkson Avenue to the south, New York Avenue to the east, and Ocean Avenue/Prospect Park to the west. Prospect Lefferts Gardens was designated a NYC Landmark area in 1979 and called the Prospect Lefferts Gardens Historic District.

txt_negFacts.title: Prospect Park Zoo
txt_negFacts.fact: The Prospect Park Zoo is a 12-acre (4.9 ha) zoo located off Flatbush Avenue on the eastern side of Prospect Park, Brooklyn, New York City. As of 2016, the zoo houses 864 animals representing about 176 species, and as of 2007, it averages 300,000 visitors annually.

txt_negFacts.title: Prospect Park (Brooklyn)
txt_negFacts.fact: Egbert Viele began drawing plans for "Mount Prospect Park", as the space was initially called, and published his proposal in 1861. The park was to straddle Flatbush Avenue and include Prospect Hill, as well as the land now occupied by the Brooklyn Public Library, Brooklyn Botanic Garden, and Brooklyn Museum.

txt_negFacts.title: Lefferts-Laidlaw House
txt_negFacts.fact: The Lefferts-Laidlaw House is a historic villa located in the Brooklyn neighborhood of Wallabout, New York City, New York. Built around 1840, the house is a two-story frame building in the temple-fronted Greek Revival style.

txt_negFacts.fact: On Lafayette Avenue can be found both the Emmanuel Baptist Church, completed in 1887, and the Joseph Steele or Steele-Skinner House of 1812, while Clinton Avenue offers the Church of St. Luke and St. Matthew (1891) and the Royal Castle Apartments, completed in 1912.

txt_negFacts.title: Prospect Park (Brooklyn)
txt_negFacts.fact: Prospect Park is an urban park in Brooklyn, New York City. The park is situated between the neighborhoods of Park Slope, Prospect Heights, Prospect Lefferts Gardens, Flatbush, and Windsor Terrace, and is adjacent to the Brooklyn Museum, Grand Army Plaza, and the Brooklyn Botanic Garden.

txt_negFacts.title: Lefferts Historic House
txt_negFacts.fact: The Lefferts Historic House is located within Prospect Park in Brooklyn, New York City. Built circa 1783, it is the former home of enslaved persons and the family of Continental Army Lieutenant Pieter Lefferts.

txt_negFacts.title: Park Slope
txt_negFacts.fact: Park Slope is a neighborhood in northwestern Brooklyn, New York City, within the area once known as South Brooklyn. Park Slope is roughly bounded by Prospect Park and Prospect Park West to the east, Fourth Avenue to the west, Flatbush Avenue to the north, and Prospect Expressway to the south.

txt_negFacts.title: Prospect Park Zoo

txt_negFacts.title: Prospect Park (Brooklyn)

txt_negFacts.title: Prospect Park (Brooklyn)

txt_negFacts.title: Andromache
txt_negFacts.fact: In Greek mythology, Andromache (; Ancient Greek: Ἀνδρομάχη, Andromákhē [andromákʰɛ͜ɛ]) was the wife of Hector, daughter of Eetion, and sister to Podes. She was born and raised in the city of Cilician Thebe, over which her father ruled.

txt_negFacts.title: Family life and children of Vladimir I
txt_negFacts.fact: Rogneda of Polotsk is the best known of Vladimir's Varangian pagan wives. The Primary Chronicle mentions three of Rogneda's sons - Izyaslav of Polotsk (+1001), Vsevolod of Volhynia (+ca 995), and Yaroslav the Wise.

txt_negFacts.title: Rogneda (opera)
txt_negFacts.fact: Skul'da shows him a vision in which Vladimir commands the people to drown the idol of Perun into the river. txt_negFacts.title: Andromache
txt_negFacts.fact: However, Andromache is seen in Iliad 6 in an unusual place for the traditional housewife, standing before the ramparts of Troy (6.370–373). Traditional gender roles are breached as well, as Andromache gives Hector military advice (6.433–439).

txt_negFacts.title: Rogneda (opera)

txt_negFacts.title: Yaroslav the Wise

txt_negFacts.title: Hector
txt_negFacts.fact: According to Homer his wife Andromache, carrying in her arms her son Astyanax, intercepts Hector at the gate, pleading with him not to go out for her sake as well as his son's.

txt_negFacts.title: Andromache

txt_negFacts.title: Echinacea purpurea
txt_negFacts.fact: Echinacea purpurea (eastern purple coneflower, purple coneflower, hedgehog coneflower, or echinacea) is a North American species of flowering plant in the sunflower family. txt_negFacts.title: Echinacea
txt_negFacts.fact: As with any herbal preparation, individual doses of Echinacea may vary significantly in chemical composition. Inconsistent process control in manufactured echinacea products may involve poor inter- and intra-batch homogeneity, species or plant part differences, variable extraction methods, and contamination or adulteration with other products, leading to potential for substantial product variability.

txt_negFacts.title: Antheraea polyphemus
txt_negFacts.fact: In the late 1950s, amateur lepidopterist Gary Botting hybridized the Polyphemus moth (then known as Telea polyphemus) with Antheraea yamamai from Japan and, later, Antheraea mylitta from India by transferring the pheromone-producing scent sacs from female "T. polyphemus" to the Antheraea females and allowing T. polyphemus males to mate with them.

txt_negFacts.title: Antheraea polyphemus
txt_negFacts.fact: The resultant hybrids were displayed in his winning U.S. National Science Fair exhibit "Intergeneric hybridization among giant silk moths". After Botting consulted with genetic statistician J.B.S. Haldane and his wife, entomologist Helen Spurway, the Polyphemus moth was reclassified, becoming Antheraea polyphemus.

txt_negFacts.fact: Franklin's decision to back Wilson over Theodore Roosevelt in the general election alienated some members of his family, although Theodore himself was not offended.

txt_negFacts.title: Roosevelt Franklin
txt_negFacts.fact: Franklin usually appears in scenes with his mother, voiced by Loretta Long, who plays Susan on the series, and Roosevelt frequently recites poetry.

txt_negFacts.title: Eleanor Roosevelt
txt_negFacts.fact: After flying with Earhart, Roosevelt obtained a student permit but did not further pursue her plans to learn to fly. Franklin was not in favor of his wife becoming a pilot.

txt_negFacts.title: Paralytic illness of Franklin D. Roosevelt
txt_negFacts.fact: The Secret Service commonly destroyed photographs they caught being taken in this manner; however, there were occasional exceptions. Only two photographs exist of Roosevelt in a wheelchair.

txt_negFacts.title: Franklin D. Roosevelt
txt_negFacts.fact: In mid-1902, Franklin began courting his future wife Eleanor Roosevelt, with whom he had been acquainted as a child. Eleanor and Franklin were fifth cousins, once removed, and Eleanor was a niece of Theodore Roosevelt.

txt_negFacts.title: Franklin D. Roosevelt
txt_negFacts.fact: Franklin contemplated divorcing Eleanor, but Sara objected strongly and Lucy would not agree to marry a divorced man with five children. Franklin and Eleanor remained married, and Roosevelt promised never to see Lucy again.

txt_negFacts.title: Franklin D. Roosevelt
txt_negFacts.fact: Franklin and Eleanor remained married, and Roosevelt promised never to see Lucy again. Eleanor never truly forgave him, and their marriage from that point on was more of a political partnership.

txt_negFacts.title: Roosevelt Franklin
txt_negFacts.fact: His name is a word play on the name of the late U.S. President Franklin Roosevelt, with the first and last names reversed.
